review_blob:
Great beer.  Very rich.  Dominating characteristic wasnt hops, but sweetness and alcohol.  I would have liked a little more bitterness.
Big thick head in my glass. Definitely need to let this one warm up a bit out of the fridge.
Delicious beer.  Reminded me somewhat of Dogfish 90.  However, Hop Henge is much smoother. Alcohol warmth without bite.

You have to like ABs intent here.  But, this combines the negative parts of both Guiness and Bud, with a certain Mickeys skunkiness.  I had just a 2 oz. taster, but literally needed to choke 1.5 oz down.  The beer looks great and has no real aroma, good or bad.  But it just tastes terrible.

Both piney and citrus hops flavors.  Very bitter, but the complexity makes it somewhat less brutal than the Ruination.  Smells great, tastes great.  I would like to see this beer stay in Stones lineup.

My lovely wife brought home 3 bottles of this for me.  I hadnt tried the beer in a while and was somewhat reluctant to try again.  However, the first two bottles were great.  A good balance between the chocolate, bitterness and sweetness.  But, the third bottle tasted completely out of whack.  The choco-sweetness was somewhat nauseating.  Perhaps I was just in a different mindset between bottles 1&2 and #3.  But after #3, I dont think I will drink this one again.

It appears that Inversion replaces the old Quail Springs IPA, and thats a good thing in my opinion.  I always thought it was about a toss up between Mirror Pond & QS in terms of hopiness.
Inversion IPA is definitely hoppy, strong orange/grapefruit citrus throughout.  Inversions alcohol is much more in the IPA range than was QS. A very enjoyable IPA, and a good replacement for what once was a single low point in Deschutess standard lineup.

The tap handle for this one was labeled "Big Homo IPA," as in a double version of their normal Homo Erectus IPA.  Like many other doble-IPAs, Homo is like a glass of grapefruit juice, in a good way.  Oily, citrusy hops with some balancing sweetness.  The alcohol was largely masked.  I really enjoyed it.

Drinking on tap as I write.  It calls itself an oatmeal, but as RB has it classified, its definitely sweeter than most oatmeal stouts Ive had.  Complex flavors, as previous reviewers have noted, but not outlandish.  Good stuff.

Oh man, this was bad.  I proudly bought a half-rack of this swill for National Corndog Day (www.corndogday.com), the bylaws of which forbid bottled beer.  I chose in the cooler from between regular Schmidt and PBR, thinking the proximity to PBR might help.  I crack the can of Schmidt Ice with the first dog of NCD...  The corndog was delicious, the beer was atrocious.  I mean real bad.  Taste was overcooked rice & corn.  Mouth-feel was liked thinned vegetable oil.  Schmidty Ice made the Miller High Life which followed it actually taste like the champagene of beers.  I had a headache from just one.
A solid daily drinker.  Great pale ale.  This might be just as hoppy as Deschutess IPA.

This ones among my 10 favorites.  Chewy stout goodness, with coffee and chocolate notes.  I have a tough time comparing Obsidian to other stouts.  It has the body of some lesser Imperial Stouts, but less bitter and without a pronounced alcohol bite.
A very tasty, easy-drinking but high-quality beer.  Beautiful color and perfect amount of hop for the style.  Too bad that Deschutes doesnt make this beer all year round.

I drank several of these during our Feb. 2006 visit.  This was a good and balanced stout with a great body.  It reminded me somewhat of Guiness Extra, but a little sweeter.  I drink this one on the mainland if available.

This was actually labeled a porter when we were there Feb. 2006.  While my wife and brother liked this beer, I did not.  Too sweet without appreciable balance of hops or anything else.  The coconut flavor was that of getting sunscreen in your mouth.  The coconut aroma was actually nice.  But did not taste good.
I didnt expect to be bored by a $4, 15% bottle of beer.  The color is very light and unclouded.  Little aroma.  Not bad, but I dont think Ill buy again.

12oz bottle from Ks Beverage in Bellevue.  As other have said, somewhat unique barleywine.  Sweeter than I care for, and without a pronounced hop or alcohol bite.  A decent barleywine but not superb.  However, after meeting brewer at a beerfest, glad to see Hood Canal makng more beers.

2005 Edition -- I think is much improved over 04.  Malt and hops are better balanced, without the nearly overpowering sweetness that some Snow Caps have had.  Im definitely back buying a case or two this year after largely skipping Snow cap the last few years.

Had on draft in Hartsfield airport.  Bartender warned me, "This is pretty hoppy."  Didnt bother to reply, "Dont worry, Im from Seattle."  While certainly not mouth puckering, its got a good hop flavor.  A pretty tasty beer, and about the best Ive had in the South.
For the price ($6.99 - $7.99 a sixer up the street), this is a pretty solid Imp Stout.

Thank you sir, may I have another?
Actually had DB before ever try regular Bastard, which would be about the only thing to make AB seem a let down.  Marketing aside, very aggressive, almost mouth numbingly so.
Doesnt fit my tastes for a barleywine.  Still, an interesting beer.  Warm, almost hot alcohol.  Peppery nose, and a nearly pineapple essense.
Near perfection.  Completely pleasing in all respects.  This is what a high quality beers should aspire to.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Didnt care for this at all.  Odd flavor, strange finish.  Im chalking up to just not getting the Baltic porter style.
I enjoyed this beer a great deal.  Better than BBays limperial outmealer, much better.  Good, thick mouthfeel.  Great chocolate finish.
I might disagree with the deScription of "intensely hopped," particularly among other PNW IPAs.  But it was a solid, if somewhat boring, IPA.  Citrusy, light carbonation.

beer_brewer_name: Yakima Brewing And Malting Co./Bert Grants Real Ales
review_blob: Accomplishes the bitterness goal, delicious hop flavor & aroma.  However, light in body, and I like my super-hoppy beers to have a little more Vitamin A.  It was good to try, but probably wont go out of my way to get again.
Alcohol was pronounced.  A good quality, enjoyable beer.  But, at $4.99/22oz, I will opt for Old Rasputin or Rogue's ImpStout next time.
This is what I ask for when I want a "light" beer.  Enjoyable, easy drinking, and quality.
Very tasty.  Impressive pour with a nice thick head.  Good smell from across the room. Hoppy stout
Great, easy drinking micro.  Solid flavor & aroma while remaining light enough to drink while "mowing the lawn."  Visit Orchard Street if you are in Bellingham, great food.
Good for a factory beer.  The only pilsner I drink
The only decent stuff from Widmer, in my opinion.
